05068nam a22007575i 9781503608771DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018033656  a97815036087717 a10.1515/97815036087712doi  a(DE-B1597)563843  a(OCoLC)1112302297  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHD1537.P18bR59 2019 4aHD1537.P18 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a333.3/1549141 aRizvi, Mubbashir A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ethics of Staying :bSocial Movements and Land Rights Politics in Pakistan /cMubbashir A. Rizvi. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia in Motion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface. From Farmers to Terrorists -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Masters, Not Friends -- tChapter 1. Politics as Process in Okara Military Farms -- tChapter 2. The Afterlife of Colonial Infrastructure -- tChapter 3. What Remains Buried Under Property? -- tChapter 4. Movement and Mobilization -- tChapter 5. Solidarities, Fault Lines, and the Scale of Struggle -- tCoda. The Ethics of Staying -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe military coup that brought General Pervez Musharraf to power as Pakistan's tenth president resulted in the abolition of a century-old sharecropping system that was rife with corruption. In its place the military regime implemented a market reform policy of cash contract farming. Ostensibly meant to improve living conditions for tenant farmers, the new system, instead, mobilized one of the largest, most successful land rights movements in South Asia—still active today. In The Ethics of Staying, Mubbashir A. Rizvi presents an original framework for understanding this major social movement, called the Anjuman Mazarin Punjab (AMP). This group of Christian and Muslim tenant sharecroppers, against all odds, successfully resisted Pakistan military's bid to monetize state-owned land, making a powerful moral case for land rights by invoking local claims to land and a broader vision for subsistence rights. The case of AMP provides a unique lens through which to examine state and society relations in Pakistan, one that bridges literatures from subaltern studies, military and colonial power, and the language of claim-making. Rizvi also offers a glimpse of Pakistan that challenges its standard framing as a hub of radical militancy, by opening a window into to the everyday struggles that are often obscured in the West's terror discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCivil-military relationszPakistanzPunjab. 0aLand reformzPakistanzPunjab. 0aLand tenurezPakistanzPunjab. 0aPeasantsxPolitical activityzPakistanzPunjab. 0aSocial movementszPakistanzPunjab. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology of the State.  aColonial Infrastructure.  aLand Rights.  aPolitical Anthropology.  aSocial Movement.  aSouth Asian Studies.  aSubaltern Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360877140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503608771423C